[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    175[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    176[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m3[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m An adversary with physical access to the rolling cart could record audio designed to trigger classifier override and play it through the device's speaker (or simulate it through a nearby speaker) during a clinician's session.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    177[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    178[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mThe recipe correctly elevates strict validation: Step 3B's "validate the intent against the configured taxonomy. Lex generally returns configured intents only, but defensive validation is appropriate for any classifier" and Step 3C's "IF bedrock_result.intent IN INTENT_TAXONOMY AND bedrock_result.confidence > BEDROCK_FALLBACK_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD" framing. This is the correct first-line defense (out-of-taxonomy outputs are coerced to "unknown"). But the prompt-injection risk goes beyond out-of-taxonomy outputs: a successful injection that produces a configured intent with an attacker-chosen patient slot value (e.g., the attacker's chosen target patient) is the more concerning case. The attacker's goal is not to produce an unknown intent; it is to produce a valid intent against the wrong patient.[K
